    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">To understand it in detail one needs to understand what convolution and pooling are. Both of these concepts are borrowed from the field of Computer Vision and are defined below.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content7 cid-ttbhFZC4Ql" id="content7-8" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
        <div class="container"><div class="row justify-content-center"><div class="col-12 col-md-9"><blockquote><p class="ff4"><strong>Convolution</strong>: Convolution operates on two signals (in 1D) or two images (in 2D): you can think of one as the “input” signal (or image), and the other (called the kernel) as a “filter” on the input image, producing an output image (so convolution takes two images as input and produces a third as output). [5]In layman terms it takes in an input signal and applies a filter over it, essentially multiplies the input signal with the kernel to get the modified signal. Mathematically, a convolution of two functions f and g is defined as</p></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
